lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-XxNYO eWQzGj pf-18_"><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-19_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-21_">Alcohol Awareness Week, coordinated by Alcohol Change UK, is a significant annual event in the United Kingdom. With the participation of public health teams, workplaces, medical facilities, and community groups, this week aims to raise awareness, campaign for change, and promote discussions surrounding alcohol consumption.<br>
 <br>In this blog, we will delve into the importance of Alcohol Awareness Week and explore the profound impact alcohol can have on mental health.<br> 
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-22_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-24_">Alcohol and cost
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_cost_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649239" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_cost_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649239 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_cost_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649239 320w" width="2741" height="1876" alt="Alcohol and cost - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Alcohol and cost - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-25_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-26_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-28_">This year's theme is "Alcohol and Cost", highlighting the significant impact of alcohol on both personal and societal levels. The harm caused by alcohol has far-reaching consequences, impacting millions of people annually through health issues, financial struggles, relationship breakdowns, and family troubles. It also places immense pressure on vital public services such as the NHS, emergency services, police, and workplaces, resulting in significant social costs estimated at a staggering Â£21 billion per year (HM Government, 2018).<br><br>The cost of living crisis has further driven some people to rely on harmful drinking as a coping mechanism. However, it doesn't have to be this way. By taking steps to make a change and with improved support and prevention, we can reduce the financial burden on public services and the loss of lives caused by alcohol.<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-29_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-31_">Alcohol and mental health
</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649380" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649380 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_and_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649380 320w" width="2880" height="1920" alt="Alcohol and mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Alcohol and mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-32_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-33_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-35_">Alcohol is the most widely used recreational drug in the UK and often the only one individuals consume. The relationship between alcohol and mental health is intricate. While some individuals may turn to alcohol to cope with symptoms of anxiety and depression, excessive drinking tends to worsen these conditions. Managing one's drinking habits and seeking appropriate support are vital in maintaining good mental health.
<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-36_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-38_">The impact on mental health


</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_impact_on_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649517" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_impact_on_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649517 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_impact_on_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649517 320w" width="3072" height="1728" alt="The impact on mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="The impact on mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-39_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-40_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-42_">Nearly 25% of people in the UK experience some mental health problem each year. Alcohol has often been described as the UK's favourite coping mechanism, with many individuals resorting to it to alleviate stress, anxiety, depression, or other mental health issues.<br><br>However, it is important to recognize that excessive drinking can worsen these conditions over time. While alcohol may offer temporary relief and a fleeting sense of euphoria, its effects are short-lived and prolonged; heavy drinking can have detrimental effects in the long run.<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-43_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-45_">Areas where alcohol can affect mental health  



</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Areas_where_alcohol_can_affect_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649680" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Areas_where_alcohol_can_affect_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649680 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Areas_where_alcohol_can_affect_mental_health_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649680 320w" width="2289" height="1807" alt="Areas where alcohol can affect mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Areas where alcohol can affect mental health - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-46_"/><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-jHkVzv gbyaRg pf-47_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-48_"><b>Worsening symptoms</b> - Overusing alcohol can contribute to the deterioration of mental health problems, particularly leading to low mood and heightened anxiety.</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-50_"><b>Post-drinking effects</b> -&nbsp;Hangovers following excessive alcohol consumption can induce feelings of depression and anxiety, adding to the challenges individuals face.</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-52_"><b>Underlying issues </b>- Using alcohol as a coping mechanism often fails to address the root causes of mental health problems, preventing individuals from seeking appropriate treatment.</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-54_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-56_">Finding the right approach




</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_the_right_approach_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649814" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_the_right_approach_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649814 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_the_right_approach_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649814 320w" width="2880" height="1920" alt="Finding the right approach - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Finding the right approach - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-57_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-58_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-60_">It is advisable to adhere to the Chief Medical Officers' guidelines, which recommend not exceeding 14 units of alcohol per week. This figure translates to approximately six pints of lager or six standard glasses of wine spread out over three or more days, with several alcohol-free days included.<br><br>Some individuals may find moderate alcohol consumption manageable, while others may benefit from abstaining entirely to improve their mental health symptoms. Open discussions with healthcare professionals, such as your doctor or local alcohol support services, can provide valuable guidance tailored to your specific circumstances. <br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-61_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-63_">Seeking support




</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Seeking_support_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649916" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Seeking_support_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688649916 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Seeking_support_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688649916 320w" width="2688" height="1541" alt="Seeking support - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Seeking support - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-64_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-65_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-67_">If you're experiencing mental health problems or alcohol-related issues, you must reach out for help. Consult your GP for guidance and consider utilising reputable resources such as Mind and Alcohol Change UK.<br> <br>Organisations like Adfam and Al-Anon provide support and resources for individuals affected by a loved one's drinking. Connecting with others who understand your experiences can offer valuable support.<br>
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-68_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-70_">Conclusion
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_Awareness_Week_Understanding_the_impact_on_mental_health_-_Conclusion_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688650104" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_Awareness_Week_Understanding_the_impact_on_mental_health_-_Conclusion_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1688650104 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Alcohol_Awareness_Week_Understanding_the_impact_on_mental_health_-_Conclusion_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1688650104 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Alcohol Awareness Week Understanding the impact on mental health - Conclusion - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Alcohol Awareness Week Understanding the impact on mental health - Conclusion - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-71_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-72_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-74_">Alcohol Awareness Week serves as a crucial opportunity to shed light on the impact of alcohol on mental health. While alcohol may offer temporary relief, its prolonged use can worsen mental health symptoms and hinder overall well-being.<br><br>By understanding the risks and seeking appropriate support, individuals can take proactive steps toward maintaining their mental health and making informed decisions regarding alcohol consumption. Remember, small changes in drinking habits and access to the proper support can profoundly impact overall well-being.<br>
